{"title":"Rethinking Negative Instances for Generative Named Entity Recognition","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"Generative NER methods typically use entity-centric training that ignores non-entity tokens, limiting contextual learning and weakening label boundaries. This leads to unlabeled, noisy, and boundary errors and poor zero-shot generalization.","method":"GNER introduces a token-by-token instruction-tuning schema that labels every token in the sentence, explicitly incorporating negative instances ('O') as context and adding BIO tagging to strengthen boundaries. The prompt pairs each token with its predicted label, with regularization via class-order shuffling and external entity sampling. This reduces noisy and boundary errors (Table 1) and yields strong gains in zero-shot NER, e.g., LLaMA-7B improves by ~12.7 F1 over UniNER on CrossNER while sharing the same backbone and data (Table 2; lines 177, 101–112, 127–129, 261)."},{"problem":"Including context and BIO labels lengthens generations, causing additions/omissions/substitutions that misalign outputs with the source text. Standard LCS post-processing is slow (O(N^2)) and brittle, making conversion to structured entities inaccurate and inefficient.","method":"They propose an optimized LCS Matching algorithm tailored to NER that parses x(y) pairs with regex, aligns generated tokens to the input via hierarchical matching—trivial and omission cases in O(N), and a fast LCS in O(N log N)—and adds Back Tokenization to handle vocabulary/OOV mismatches. This accelerates alignment up to 17.3× on long sequences and improves accuracy; removing Back Tokenization or the LCS step degrades performance (Tables 5–6; lines 187–193, 415–418, 267–274, 279–286)."},{"problem":"Beam search often fails or degrades performance in entity-centric generative NER because it encourages repeated or inconsistent answers and cannot revise early mistakes.","method":"Under GNER’s token-by-token schema, beam search enables a self-correction mechanism: later context can revise earlier token labels within beams. Increasing beam size consistently improves zero-shot F1 across backbones, whereas UniNER’s performance declines with larger beams. Case studies show corrections from 'O' to proper B/I labels when later tokens provide decisive cues (Table 7 and Fig. 6/Table 10; lines 317–321, 288–298, 299–307, 474–491)."}]}
